Due to inclement weather, Martinsville ISD will be moving to asynchronous remote instruction ONLY for Thursday, August 27 and Friday, August 28. Campus facilities will be closed on those days, though students and their families are welcome to use our WiFi in the new parking lot area. Also, buses will NOT run Thursday and Friday to align with the move to asynchronous remote instruction. No meals will be served Thursday or Friday.

If your child has issues with the internet or electricity we understand the issue and can address on Monday.

Again, all students PK-12 will move to asynchronous remote instruction on Thursday August, 27 and Friday, August 28.

Please stay safe!

post_text:
We are so excited to have our Pirates back on campus tomorrow! Just a few reminders about morning drop-off and after school car rider pick-up.
1. Please stay in your vehicles for the morning drop off and evening pick-up. We will not be walking students inside or picking them up at the doors during Phase 1 of our reopening plan.
2. Chief Gilcrease will be in the parking lot tomorrow morning to help direct traffic. We will be utilizing the new parking lot to maximize traffic flow.
3. During after school car rider pick-up, please remember the outside lane is for secondary pick-up (Grades 7-12), and the inside lane is only for elementary pick-up.
4. The middle lane for both morning and evening is used for the flow of traffic.

Please allow extra time in the morning and evening this week. The first few days of school are always the busiest in the car rider lines.

See you all in the morning!

post_text:
This is an important update regarding the beginning of the 2020-2021 school year.

Virtual learning commitment forms are due back to the school on Tuesday, August 11, 2020. The forms can be found on the MISD website. If you have trouble finding the form or do not have ability to access the form, please contact the school during business hours and you can fill out the form at the school. Remember that commitment is for a minimum of a six week grading period.

Also, we want to update the community that based on the most recent guidance from the Texas Education Agency, Martinsville ISD will be requiring masks for ALL students PK-12, faculty and staff, as well as visitors at all times with exceptions noted in our reopening documents. This documents will be updated to reflect this change as soon as possible. We understand that this may cause slight inconveniences, but is the current best practice to keep students, faculty, staff, parents, and community members safe.

#PirateNationTX

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
Student Supply Pick-Up
Wednesday, May 20th, 8:00am-12:00pm

Next Wednesday, May 20th, we will have a drive-through line for students to pickup-up their school supplies, athletic supplies from their athletic lockers, end of the year awards, spring pictures, etc. Everything will be delivered to your car as you drive through the line. Please do not get out of your car.
If you have library books or payment for the cafeteria, you may drop that off with the teachers who will have a small bin so there is no hand to hand contact.

Line Location
PreK-2nd grade: Bus Drop Off
3rd-6th grade: Big Gym Next to Admin Office
7th-12th grade: Commons Area

We are looking forward to being able to tell everyone goodbye for the summer and to give them smiles and hugs from afar.

Thank You!

post_text:
April 18, 2020

Dear MISD Parents, Students, and Staff,
Yesterday, Governor Greg Abbott declared that all Texas schools will stay closed for the remainder of the year. Martinsville ISD will continue our current process of distributing and collecting student work packets until further notice.

The Commissioner of Education, Mike Morath, will be providing guidance to school districts on graduation ceremony options in the near future. We will consider all options available and notify our senior students and parents as soon as possible.

Please stay safe by observing social distancing and other recommendations by health care officials.

For the latest information related to MISD operations, visit our:
Website: www.MartinsvilleISD.com
Facebook: www.facebook.com/MartinsvilleISD
Twitter: @PirateNationTX
Instagram: @PirateNationTX and local media outlets for updated information.

Sincerely,

David Simmons, Ph.D.
Superintendent of Schools

**Instructional Packet Turn In Date**

The first round of instructional packets were going to be turned in this coming Friday; however, that date has now changed to Monday, April 6th. There will be NO Friday, April 3rd, instructional packet turn in. Please don’t come to the school on Friday to turn in instructional packets because there will be no one available.

This date change will allow students more time to work on their instructional packets. It will also allow parents/students to make one trip to the school because they can turn in the current instructional packet as they get the new instructional packet on Monday, April 6th.

Also, a reminder that breakfast/lunch will be available for curb side pickup on Monday, April 6th, 7:30-10:30am.

Thank you!

post_text:
Elementary students went on a Kindness Adventure this Tuesday morning! Abraham and his buddy Ned put on an amazing show all about showing kindness to others.

Our school got the assembly for free because we’re hosting a Kindness Sale. With each purchase, you help keep kindness going in three ways:
1. Gives your child a kindness reminder
2. Sends another Kindness Adventure to other schools for free
3. Provides income for artisans in Kenya

***Each school that hosts the assembly and the Kindness Sale is helping provide clean water for the kids in Kenya. Learn more about this year’s well project at KindnessAdventure.com/giving.html .
Sale starts tomorrow, Wednesday, and will last for five days. The sale will be in the commons 7:30-8:00 a.m.

post_text: The 5th and 6th graders did a fundraiser called “Change for Change in Australia” to help with all the wildfires going on there. They were very successful by going the extra mile and collecting money from their neighborhoods, ball games, and selling donated products to go towards this fundraiser. They raised $1,163.68 which will all be sent to the Fauna Rescue Center of South Australia. We are grateful for such a giving community and appreciate everyone for the support.￼

EARLY RELEASE FRIDAY: Due to forecasted severe weather tomorrow, Friday, January 10, 2020, Martinsville ISD will be on an early release schedule. School will begin at the normal time. Elementary will release at 12:45 PM and junior high and high school will release at 1:00 PM.

We are taking these steps in order to be proactive and ensure the safety of each of our students, faculty, staff, and parents. We will continue to monitor the forecast and update you if any changes to this schedule are made.

#PirateNationTX

We are excited to have our first annual Book Fair at the Christmas Music Program. It will be set-up in the cafeteria and will open at 5:30pm. It will close when the music program starts but it will reopen after the program is done. What a great time to purchase some wonderful books for your kids or Christmas gifts for loved ones.

We are looking forward to a fun night!

Rex Perry Autoplex is at Rex Perry Autoplex.
November 8, 2019 at 2:11 PM · Nacogdoches, TX ·

We’ve partnered with Martinsville ISD for the month of November as the high school students participate in a safe driving competition focused on distracted driving.

The students download an app that deducts points as it registers they are on their phone while the car is going 10mph or above. Gift cards are given out to participants weekly, and the student with the most points at the end of the month gets a $150 gift card!

We are encouraged by the school’s action in taking car safety seriously while also ￼keeping it fun!

Tune in weekly to for updates on how the completion is going!

post_text: Martinsville ISD is saddened by the passing of Mrs. Marie Green (1933-2019) last month. Mrs. Green was an ardent supporter of Martinsville ISD, as well as many other organizations to which she gave a great deal of time, effort, and expertise. She served the school for a number of years, with ten of those serving on the Board of Trustees. As a trustee, she served as an officer of the board for a majority of her tenure. She made a motion to call for a bond election for what is now known as the administration building in 1998. At the time of its opening, the facility was called the greatest investment in education in the history of Martinsville. This is just one testament to the impact that Mrs. Green had on the Martinsville community. A memorial service for Mrs. Green will be held at Martinsville Baptist Church at 11 AM on Saturday, November 9, 2019.

post_text:
We have had an amazing trip visiting NASA and Galveston! We have learned so much and laughed along the way which is always awesome! The kids loved every minute of the NASA exhibits, beach time, pool, crabbing, and the ferry ride. Our kids were the absolute best which is no surprise. They received compliments everywhere we went. ❤️

A big huge thanks to Mrs. Susan Mueller! Wow, I can’t even begin to explain how organized she had each and everything. Amazing! Taking the 6th grade class on an overnight trip is no way an easy task; however, she made it look so easy.

Thank you to the following for chaperoning: Mrs. Jessica Dillard, Mrs. Michelle Adams, Mrs. Angela Quinn, Mrs. Briley Latham, Mrs. Linda Fenton, Mr. Shane Randall, and Mr. Mike Montario. Y’all are awesome and oh so brave.

A special thank you to our fabulous bus driver Mr. Collin Davis who also helped us chaperon. We are thankful for him!

post_text: At 9:00 AM today, Martinsville ISD conducted a lockdown drill. Chief Steve Gilcrease on the drill, "I'm very pleased to let everyone know that our drill was a 100% success. MISD was a ghost town. It was as if the campus were empty. This just reaffirms that MISD is the safest school in the county." We as a district strive to keep our students, faculty, and staff safe. #PirateNationTX

post_text:
Mrs. Joni, our Registered Nurse, came to Pre-K today with her friend "Sneezy Simon" to show us how easily germs spread when we do not cover our coughs and sneezes.

She put some glitter "germs" on her hand and had the kids shake her hand and then shake a friends hand to see how easily we spread germs and the importance of washing our hands.

We are thankful to have Mrs. Joni at our school!

Martinsville art was well represented at the Pineywoods Fair! We had 20 entries total.

Jasmine Murphy won 3rd place in the youth painting division.
Jazmin Mendez placed 6th in the youth painting division.

Shannon also got two 2nd place ribbons for her photographs.

All of our art looked awesome displayed at the fair.
Good job, artists!

post_text: Martinsville ISD is saddened by the passing of Mrs. Margaret Hardy on September 30, 2019. Mrs. Hardy was in a very exclusive group of people who both attended Martinsville school and taught there. She taught at Martinsville for over 25 years from 1962-1989. Her impact on the students and community of Martinsville would be impossible to measure. We invite you to share this post and comment memories of Mrs. Hardy that you have. Her full obituary will be posted in the comments. She was a true embodiment of the spirit of #PirateNationTX

Grades: PreK, Kinder, 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th
Tuesday, September 17th, 2019

We will have our annual vision and hearing screenings next Tuesday, September 17th. The Lions Club will be helping us out with the vision screenings. They are very advanced in their screening process and we are excited to have their assistance. The form below will be sent home today and it will need to be returned to school before the vision test can be administered. Thank You!

Box Tops & Coke Reward Points

Some info on the changes in Boxtops! Honestly, this is easier! Clip if the Boxtop is on the product. Scan your receipt if it's not! Or send in your receipts and we will get someone to scan them!

We are excited to say that we received our first check from the Coke Reward program and it's an easy way for our school to earn money. We appreciate everyone's support! We are excited!

Meet the Teacher
Mrs. Chandler our Registered Nurse will be available at Meet the Teacher, Thursday, August 22nd, 5:30-7:00. She will have a table set up in the commons.

If you need to drop off medications, supplies, or shot records, she will have the appropriate forms for you to sign. Please remember that if you are dropping off a prescription drug, the medication must be in the original bottle with the directions and physician information on the prescription label.

We are looking forward to seeing everyone! Thank You!

shared_text:
Martinsville FFA
August 6, 2019 at 11:07 AM ·

Good morning everyone!

Hope everyone is enjoying their summer, but school is closing in. Mrs. Cobb will be doing the Floral Arrangement of the Month Club again and wanted to send the flyer out early!

Order forms and money will not be due until September 30th. The prices this year are for a 3 Month- $60 and for an 8 month- $120. If you need to pay it out until then we most certainly can be accommodating.

I have attached the flyer that you can print out and bring to the office or at meet the teacher. The money and order form must be turned in together and can be turned into the front office or to me. Enjoy the few days you have left and we look forward to seeing everyone when school starts! Also don't forget to consider us if you need floral work done. And if you have any old vases laying around you don't need, we recycle!

Thanks for supporting our kids!

As we get up and ready for the first day of Convention this morning we have an update on FFA Rodeo!

Hunter Dillard and his partner were 3rd place in Round 1 yesterday and a no catch in Round 2. We found out this morning they qualified for the Finals and will be roping today at 5pm! We will keep you up to date as the day goes on. Congrats Hunter on making it to the Finals!

shared_text:
Stephen F. Austin State University School of Theatre
June 14, 2019 at 5:28 PM ·

SummerStageFestival featured student of the day is Senior Alli Beck who is appearing in the musical The 25th Annual Putnam County Spelling Bee in the role of Olive Ostrovsky, and in The Reluctant Dragon as ½ of the Dragon. Alli is a BFA Acting Major.

What is your favorite part of being in this show?: My favorite part of Reluctant is the movement and acrobatics of being the dragon. My favorite of Putnam is the singing and humor.

What is the most challenging part of being in the show?: The most challenging part of Reluctant is puppeteer-ing a dragon and acting without facial expressions.

Why should people come see the show?: Because they're both going to be SO much fun!

Hometown: Nacogdoches, Texas

For ticketing information visit us online at http://www.finearts.sfasu.edu/purchase or call the box office at 936-468-6407. The Summer Stage Festival features the 2 shows in repertory and runs from June 27 to July 12.

Good luck you two! #PirateNationTX
